==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grunt
<hw>Grunt</hw> <pr>(gr⟦ucr⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Grunted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Grunting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>grunten</ets>; akin to
As. <ets>grunian</ets>, G. <ets>grunzen</ets>, Dan. <ets>grynte</ets>,
Sw. <ets>grymta</ets>; all prob. of imitative; or perh. akin to E.
<ets>groan</ets>.]</ety> <def>To make a deep, short noise, as a hog; to
utter a short groan or a deep guttural sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who would fardels bear,⟦br⟧
To <qex>grunt</qex> and sweat under a weary life.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Grunting ox</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
yak.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 655 --></p>

<p><ent>Grunt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Grunt
<hw>Grunt</hw> <pr>(gr⟦ucr⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
deep, guttural sound, as of a hog.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of
American food fishes, of the genus <gen>Haemulon</gen>, allied to the
snappers, as, the black grunt (<spn>Haemulon Plumieri</spn>), and the
redmouth grunt (<spn>Haemulon aurolineatus</spn>), of the Southern
United States; -- also applied to allied species of the genera
<gen>Pomadasys</gen>, <gen>Orthopristis</gen>, and
<gen>Pristopoma</gen>. Called also <altname>pigfish</altname>,
<altname>squirrel fish</altname>, and <altname>grunter</altname>; -- so
called from the noise it makes when taken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A U. S. infantryman; -- used especially of those
fighting in the war in Vietnam.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grunter</ent>⟦br⟧
